WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.869
Welcome to the session. This is the Mini Symposium on KRAS Targeted Therapies:

2
00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:05.620
Overcoming Resistance.

3
00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:10.420
I know there's a number of other kind of RAS-themed

4
00:00:10.860 --> 00:00:14.640
mini symposiums ongoing, but this is really the best one.

5
00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:18.430
So welcome. I'm here with Dr. Malhotra from City of

6
00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:22.420
Hope. She's going to do our introductions, and then we're going to

7
00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:26.240
call out the speakers, 10 minutes, and five minutes for

8
00:00:26.300 --> 00:00:30.120
questions, and hopefully end on time.

9
00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:33.800
So Dr. Malhotra is going to introduce our topic for today. Thank you, Dr. Malhotra.

10
00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:39.940
Thank you, Dr. Hong, and thank you to all of you for being here.

11
00:00:40.140 --> 00:00:43.760
We really look forward to the interesting data that will be presented

12
00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:44.340
today.

13
00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:50.520
So KRAS, all of you have already heard quite a lot about this, which

14
00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:51.300
is good.

15
00:00:52.180 --> 00:00:55.700
Currently, we only have KRAS G12C

16
00:00:55.740 --> 00:00:59.060
inhibitors approved for pre-treated lung

17
00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:02.580
cancer and colorectal cancer, either as monotherapy or with

18
00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:06.280
EGFR inhibitors. But hopefully that will change

19
00:01:06.380 --> 00:01:09.960
soon now based on all the data that we are seeing, there are a

20
00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:13.900
lot of KRAS inhibitors in development, mutation-specific

21
00:01:14.020 --> 00:01:17.800
pan-KRAS and pan-RAS. So really, what's the

22
00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:21.810
next step? So we really have to come up with effective combination strategies

23
00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:26.160
to achieve those deep and durable responses for our patients, in

24
00:01:26.200 --> 00:01:28.680
addition to minimizing toxicity.

25
00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:32.670
And then end of the day, we really have to find ways to really tailor the

26
00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:36.090
combination to the patient, to their tumor type,

27
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.200
as well as the mechanism of potential resistance.

28
00:01:40.940 --> 00:01:44.640
So in terms of mechanisms of resistance to KRAS inhibitors, they can be

29
00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:48.540
either innate or acquired molecular or

30
00:01:48.620 --> 00:01:49.140
genetic

31
00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:53.740
mechanisms, or they can be adaptive mechanisms of resistance

32
00:01:53.820 --> 00:01:57.360
really manifesting, such as epithelial to mesenchymal

33
00:01:57.740 --> 00:02:01.620
transition, just as an example. So today, we will be reviewing

34
00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:05.510
seven presentations, really presenting novel data, looking

35
00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:08.961
at different combination strategies with KRAS inhibitors.

36
00:02:09.640 --> 00:02:13.440
One potential combination strategy is to combine KRAS

37
00:02:13.480 --> 00:02:17.420
inhibitors with targeting of a downstream target,

38
00:02:17.460 --> 00:02:21.120
and we have two presentations there looking at targeting

39
00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:24.740
PIK3 as well as mTOR in addition to

40
00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:25.480
KRAS.

41
00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:30.460
The second combination strategy is to inhibit potential

42
00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:34.160
adaptive responses that can be a mechanism of

43
00:02:34.180 --> 00:02:37.860
resistance. And here we have two presentations, one looking at

44
00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:41.660
autophagy inhibition, the other looking at targeting the JAK-STAT

45
00:02:41.760 --> 00:02:45.150
pathway. And last but not the least, another combination

46
00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:48.630
strategy is to combine KRAS inhibitors with other

47
00:02:48.660 --> 00:02:52.060
drugs which leverage other cancer-associated

48
00:02:52.200 --> 00:02:56.060
vulnerabilities. And here we have three presentations, two of which

49
00:02:56.180 --> 00:02:57.840
will talk about

50
00:02:58.680 --> 00:03:02.280
targeting DNA damage repair pathway, and then one

51
00:03:02.290 --> 00:03:05.790
presentation will look at oxidative stress, especially that

52
00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:09.300
associated with KEAP1 and Nrf2 resistance.

53
00:03:10.540 --> 00:03:14.040
One request to all the speakers that please try to limit your

54
00:03:14.060 --> 00:03:17.820
presentations to 10 minutes or less so that we have five

55
00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:21.420
minutes after each presentation for question and answer.

56
00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:24.400
So without further delay, we will get started.

57
00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:27.200
Our first presentation is from Dr.

58
00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:31.560
Wen-Hsun Chang from University of North Carolina, who

59
00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:35.520
will be presenting on defining a molecular signature for

60
00:03:35.580 --> 00:03:38.880
KEAP1-Nrf2-mediated resistance to KRAS inhibition.

61
00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:40.140
Dr. Chang.

62
00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:48.020
Okay.

63
00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:53.000
First I'd like to thanks the committee for selecting me to present this talk.

64
00:03:53.020 --> 00:03:56.380
I'm really excited to share our recent progress in understanding

65
00:03:56.420 --> 00:04:00.360
KEAP1-Nrf2-mediated resistance to RAS inhibitions in both

66
00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:02.840
pancreatic cancers and lung cancers.

67
00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:09.440
We started this project really just trying to understand the resistance mechanism

68
00:04:09.500 --> 00:04:13.240
of RAS inhibitors. So we actually first conducted CRISPR screens

69
00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:16.981
using a pancreatic cancer models treated with both

70
00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:20.760
G12D inhibitor MRTX1133 or the

71
00:04:20.820 --> 00:04:24.350
multi-RAS inhibitor RMC7977. And in both

72
00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:28.480
screens, we identified that knockout of KEAP1 are

73
00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:32.400
one of the most potent drivers to promote resistance to

74
00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:35.740
RAS inhibitors in these systems. So we decided to follow that up.

75
00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:40.950
So let me tell you a little bit of the biology of the KEAP1 and Nrf2 pathways.

76
00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:44.400
So KEAP1 is a member of E3 ubiquitin ligase that

77
00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:47.880
will engage Nrf2 and promote its polyubiquitination and

78
00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:51.600
degradation. So in the normal conditions, it will basically keep the Nrf2

79
00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:55.620
expression low. And Nrf2 is a transcription factor, so it will facilitate a

80
00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:57.260
series of transcriptions.

81
00:04:58.420 --> 00:05:02.200
But in cancer cells, loss of function mutation happen on KEAP1 or

82
00:05:02.240 --> 00:05:05.720
gain of function mutation happen on Nrf2 will basically break the

83
00:05:05.780 --> 00:05:09.520
KEAP1-Nrf2 interactions. So in this case, Nrf2 will no longer be

84
00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:14.400
negatively regulated by KEAP1, and it will start to facilitate a

85
00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:17.880
series of gene transcriptions regulated cell survival or

86
00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:19.330
metabolic reprogramming.

87
00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:24.580
In fact, several study has identified that KEAP1 mutation is

88
00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:27.000
associated with resistance to RAS inhibitors.

89
00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:29.400
One of the study nicely described by Dr.

90
00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:33.360
Marcel Nagrat last years, showing that for KRAS

91
00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:37.280
G12C mutant NSCLC patient treated with adagrasib, those patient

92
00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:40.920
with KEAP1 mutation tend to perform poorly, based on the

93
00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:43.580
progression-free survival and overall survival plots here.

94
00:05:43.940 --> 00:05:46.840
And it should also be noted that the KEAP1 mutation actually represent

95
00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:50.840
15% of total NSCLC patient population, which is a

96
00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:54.220
significant patient numbers.Another study

97
00:05:54.640 --> 00:05:58.340
released from Revolution Medicine last year actually shows that for PDAC

98
00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:02.220
patients acquire resistance to erlotinib/racib, some patients actually were

99
00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:05.480
found with KEAP1 truncation, which is very likely a

100
00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:07.880
loss of function KEAP1 mutations.

101
00:06:08.420 --> 00:06:12.340
And also, study has also shown that in the Grade 3 PDAC

102
00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:16.400
tumors, based on IH staining, also found that these tumor has a lot of Nrf2

103
00:06:16.460 --> 00:06:19.580
overexpressions. So based on these clinical studies, we

104
00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:24.000
conclude that the KEAP1 Nrf2 pathway play an important role in

105
00:06:24.220 --> 00:06:28.180
not only regulating cancer progression, but also regulating sensitivity to

106
00:06:28.260 --> 00:06:29.180
RAS inhibitors.

107
00:06:30.780 --> 00:06:33.720
So we decided to get to the bottom of this mechanism.

108
00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:37.800
So we decided first to generate a KEAP1 Nrf2 stable knockout

109
00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:40.040
cell line. Here I'm showing you two examples here.

110
00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:43.580
When we knockout KEAP1, we can see a nice overexpression of

111
00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:44.200
Nrf2,

112
00:06:45.180 --> 00:06:48.850
and its transcription target NQO1 also increase as

113
00:06:48.900 --> 00:06:52.780
well. And when we are challenging these cell line with RAS inhibitor, we

114
00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:56.080
found that the KEAP1 knockout cell line become far less

115
00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:59.860
sensitive to RAS inhibitor compared to the control cell lines.

116
00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:04.420
We moved this model to the NSCLC model, which we have a KP

117
00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:04.760
tumor

118
00:07:06.520 --> 00:07:10.110
allograft model with a control knockout or a KEAP1 knockout.

119
00:07:10.220 --> 00:07:14.160
And as you can see here, the control knockout is highly sensitive to the

120
00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:17.260
G12D inhibitor shown here, but the KEAP1 knockout,

121
00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:21.730
the tumor can still slowly growing under the G12D

122
00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:25.690
inhibitor treatments. So from this experiment, we conclude that

123
00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:29.900
a KEAP1 knockout will promote the resistance to RAS inhibitor in both

124
00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:33.500
lung cancer and pancreatic cancer in vitro and in vivo.

125
00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:38.060
We then ask the question whether Nrf2 is the major player to drive the

126
00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:42.000
resistance. So we generate a KEAP1 Nrf2 double knockout cells, and

127
00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:44.500
as you can see, there are proliferation curve in green.

128
00:07:44.820 --> 00:07:48.700
Pretty much the proliferation curve with KEAP1 Nrf2 double knockout cells

129
00:07:48.800 --> 00:07:50.480
overlap with the control knockouts.

130
00:07:50.800 --> 00:07:54.240
So with that, we conclude that the Nrf2 is the major player to drive

131
00:07:54.280 --> 00:07:58.240
resistance, mediated by KEAP1 knockout.

132
00:07:58.870 --> 00:08:02.160
And since Nrf2 is a transcription factor, we then went on to

133
00:08:02.580 --> 00:08:06.460
characterize the transcriptomic change in PDAC cell line when we

134
00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:10.380
knock out KEAP1. And we did a bulk RNA sequencing

135
00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:13.820
and identify about 1,200 genes significantly upregulated

136
00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:18.090
upon KEAP1 knockout, and about 1,000 genes significantly downregulated.

137
00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:22.760
We then want to ask whether these genes are somehow related to RAS, so

138
00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:25.720
we treat these KEAP1 knockout cells with RAS inhibitors.

139
00:08:26.140 --> 00:08:29.980
And what was interesting here is that we found that these significantly upregulated

140
00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:31.360
genes upon KEAP1 knockout,

141
00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:35.780
65% remain upregulated when the RAS

142
00:08:35.941 --> 00:08:39.420
inhibitor was treated in these cell lines, and only less than

143
00:08:39.581 --> 00:08:42.980
1% of the cells become downregulated, which suggests that these

144
00:08:43.441 --> 00:08:46.900
genes were pretty much independent to RAS signaling pathways.

145
00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:52.140
So we then want to further analyze this angle, and our laboratory

146
00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:56.120
and other groups has identified that reactivation of RAS-ERK,

147
00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:00.280
activation of MYC transcription factors, and activation of TEAD transcription

148
00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:02.680
factor can promote resistance to RAS inhibitors.

149
00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:07.040
Our group also recently published these studies along with

150
00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:09.480
Paul et al. published this study.

151
00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:14.130
I compare the KEAP1-dependent transcriptome, MYC-dependent

152
00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:16.850
transcriptome, and TEAD-dependent transcriptome.

153
00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:20.620
These three RNA-Seq data set with my KEAP1 knockout data set to

154
00:09:20.680 --> 00:09:24.600
identify how much overlap they have within these four

155
00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:25.160
data sets.

156
00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:30.100
So these network analysis, each dot represent one single genes

157
00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:33.990
regulated by either RAS, MYC, or TEAD, or upregulated by

158
00:09:34.120 --> 00:09:37.930
KEAP1 knockout. You can see there's a lot of overlap between RAS, MYC, and

159
00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:41.870
TEAD, but pretty much the genes regulated by KEAP1 knockout are largely

160
00:09:41.880 --> 00:09:44.560
independent to the RAS, MYC, and TEAD.

161
00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:48.150
So that suggests that KEAP1 knockout regulated transcriptomes, that's

162
00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:54.109
pretty much distinct from the transcriptome mediated by RAS, MYC, and TEAD,

163
00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:58.280
which could also suggest that KEAP1 knockout promote resistance using

164
00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:01.900
distinct mechanisms regulated by other three progress.

165
00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:07.980
We then wanted to generate a focused gene signatures by filtering the

166
00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:11.929
top 200 coding genes from our KEAP1 knockout transcriptomes,

167
00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:16.080
and we decide to name it as a PDAC KEAP1 deficiency gene signatures.

168
00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:20.300
We cross-reference our data with the ENCODE ChIP-seq database and

169
00:10:20.360 --> 00:10:24.120
found that about 50% of the genes are direct Nrf2

170
00:10:24.130 --> 00:10:27.880
target, which means that our signature capture both direct

171
00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:30.240
Nrf2 targets and secondary target as well.

172
00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:33.600
We then look at the patient data treated with adagrasib.

173
00:10:33.720 --> 00:10:37.660
Here we have 10 patients treated with adagrasib, and for those eight

174
00:10:37.780 --> 00:10:41.600
patient who were resistant to adagrasib, we look at their sequencing data

175
00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:45.340
before receive any treatment, and these patients express

176
00:10:45.400 --> 00:10:49.280
higher gene expression of our PKD gene signature compared

177
00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:52.520
to those patient who were sensitive to the drug.

178
00:10:53.920 --> 00:10:56.940
Another data set we look at was published by Simon et al.

179
00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.980
at 2023, where they have a KRAS G12C mutant

180
00:11:01.020 --> 00:11:04.920
PDX model RNA-Seq data. And when we look at these RNA-Seq data,

181
00:11:07.780 --> 00:11:10.940
we found that the resistant PDX model has far

182
00:11:12.340 --> 00:11:16.220
higher PKD gene expressions compared to those which were

183
00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:20.220
sensitive to the drug. So from this, we conclude that our

184
00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:24.160
PKD signature is associated with resistance to

185
00:11:24.180 --> 00:11:25.140
RAS inhibitor.

186
00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:29.760
We then trying to identify a

187
00:11:30.680 --> 00:11:34.280
therapeutic strategy to overcome the resistance to

188
00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:39.460
RAS inhibitor mediated by KEAP1 loss or Nrf2 activations.

189
00:11:39.780 --> 00:11:43.600
And it has been reported that KEAP1 loss or Nrf2 activation will

190
00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:46.680
enhance the glutamine metabolism in cancer cells.

191
00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:48.700
Here I'm showing you three examples here.

192
00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:52.940
In our study, we also found that KEAP1 loss promote

193
00:11:53.060 --> 00:11:56.760
glutamine uptake and glutamate secretion in these

194
00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.500
PDAC systems that we identified.

195
00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:04.700
So we wanted to leverage these observations, and we use

196
00:12:04.780 --> 00:12:08.720
a-Glutamine metabolism inhibitor DRP104

197
00:12:08.780 --> 00:12:12.620
is a glutamine antagonist that globally targets all the

198
00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:16.480
glutamine-utilizing enzymes. So we want to use this to inhibit the

199
00:12:16.540 --> 00:12:20.320
glutamine metabolism pathways. And this drug is also being

200
00:12:20.380 --> 00:12:24.360
evaluated in several clinical trials, with especially one KPO1-NERV2

201
00:12:24.420 --> 00:12:28.360
alter NSCLC tumor that was recently launched at NYU.

202
00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:33.120
So we decided to combine this inhibitor with the RAS

203
00:12:33.140 --> 00:12:37.040
inhibitors and see if we can overcome the resistance mediated by KPO1

204
00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:38.840
loss or NERV2 activations.

205
00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:42.480
So here we move it to the in vivo model.

206
00:12:42.560 --> 00:12:44.980
Here we have three in vivo models shown here.

207
00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:48.700
We have a PDAC PDX model with NERV2

208
00:12:48.740 --> 00:12:52.360
amplification in these tumors. We have a lung cancer

209
00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:56.340
KP tumor allograft model, and in this model, we have KPO1 knockout,

210
00:12:57.020 --> 00:13:00.920
and we also have a KP tumor model expressing a dominant negative

211
00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.900
form of KPO1 R470C.

212
00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:09.260
In all three in vivo experiments, we identified that the RAS

213
00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:12.600
inhibitor plus the DRP104, the glutamine

214
00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:16.700
antagonist, can nicely suppress the tumor growth in all three

215
00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:19.140
models compared to any single agent alone.

216
00:13:19.500 --> 00:13:22.660
So we conclude that we can leverage the glutamine metabolism

217
00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:26.290
dependencies and combine the inhibitor targeting glutamine

218
00:13:26.290 --> 00:13:30.210
metabolism with RAS inhibitors as a way to target KPO1-NERV2

219
00:13:30.380 --> 00:13:31.120
alter tumors.

220
00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:34.680
And this work is in collaboration with Dr.

221
00:13:34.740 --> 00:13:37.870
Andrew Gerri, Brian Wolping, Dr. Thalis

222
00:13:37.940 --> 00:13:40.480
Papagiannakopoulos, and Kwok-Ying Wong from NYU

223
00:13:41.260 --> 00:13:42.860
with this work.

224
00:13:44.540 --> 00:13:46.360
With this, I'd like to conclude my talk.

225
00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:50.420
So I hope I can convince you that we've demonstrated KPO1 loss really

226
00:13:50.460 --> 00:13:52.700
promote resistance to RAS inhibitors.

227
00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:56.580
We identify the signatures that is associated to resistance to RAS

228
00:13:56.590 --> 00:14:00.560
inhibitor, both in patient datasets and in PDX datasets.

229
00:14:01.060 --> 00:14:05.020
And we also directly defined a transcriptome that is distinct.

230
00:14:05.900 --> 00:14:09.780
KPO1 knockout transcriptome distinct from the transcriptome regulated

231
00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:13.440
by RAS, MYC, and TED. And we showed that the

232
00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:17.200
combination of RAS inhibitor with a glutamine antagonist, DRP104,

233
00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:20.540
can potently inhibit the growth of NERV2-activated tumors.

234
00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:25.020
With that, I'd like to thank all the collaborators who contributed to this work.

235
00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:29.090
Thanks to Channing, Adrienne, Clint, and Kirsten for their support to this work.

236
00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:33.540
Addison and Stami in the lab contribute a lot on a lot of

237
00:14:33.600 --> 00:14:37.460
study here. I also like to thank the collaborator from NYU, Thalis,

238
00:14:37.980 --> 00:14:41.720
and Kwok-Ying Wong, and Alec. Our collaborator from University of Cincinnati,

239
00:14:41.980 --> 00:14:45.140
Andrew Walters, and collaborator from Dana-Farber, Andrew Gerri.

240
00:14:45.620 --> 00:14:49.510
And this work has been deposited on bioRxiv here, and this

241
00:14:49.540 --> 00:14:53.200
is my contact information, so happy to take any questions here or

242
00:14:53.240 --> 00:14:53.880
further. Thank you.

