So previous report suggested that the resistant

1504
01:29:36.650 --> 01:29:40.350
tumor cell can activate aurora kinase A signaling

1505
01:29:40.450 --> 01:29:44.430
and drive adaptive resistance, either by phosphorylating

1506
01:29:44.550 --> 01:29:48.150
CRAF and MAP kinase signaling, as well as degradation

1507
01:29:48.230 --> 01:29:51.670
of pro-apoptotic protein Bim to avoid

1508
01:29:51.810 --> 01:29:55.590
apoptosis. We tested both of these mechanism in our

1509
01:29:55.610 --> 01:29:59.470
cell line and did not observe a consistent result across the

1510
01:29:59.530 --> 01:30:01.190
panel of model we tested.

1511
01:30:02.300 --> 01:30:06.210
Well, given the role of aurora kinase A in mitotic progression, we

1512
01:30:06.290 --> 01:30:09.770
then instead hypothesized that the KRAS G12C

1513
01:30:09.780 --> 01:30:13.350
inhibition may create a mitotic vulnerability that is

1514
01:30:13.370 --> 01:30:15.610
dependent on aurora kinase A function.

1515
01:30:18.250 --> 01:30:21.870
So to test that hypothesis, we utilize the single-cell

1516
01:30:21.950 --> 01:30:25.850
time-lapse imaging together with CDK2 activity

1517
01:30:25.890 --> 01:30:29.310
to label cell cycle as well as the H2B to

1518
01:30:29.370 --> 01:30:33.070
label the cell death and track the cell after they get a

1519
01:30:33.110 --> 01:30:35.430
treatment, and this was a collaboration with Dr.

1520
01:30:35.750 --> 01:30:38.150
Spencer's group at the University of Colorado.

1521
01:30:39.390 --> 01:30:42.730
As you can see, the vehicle-treated cells cycles normally,

1522
01:30:43.310 --> 01:30:45.690
and G12C inhibitor-treated cells have marked

1523
01:30:46.330 --> 01:30:50.150
G0/G1 arrest. Aurora kinase A cause

1524
01:30:50.230 --> 01:30:53.990
prolonged G2/M arrest. The combination of cells cause a

1525
01:30:54.090 --> 01:30:57.530
lot of cell death, and the majority of the death

1526
01:30:57.630 --> 01:31:01.290
event actually happens after the mitotic arrest,

1527
01:31:01.870 --> 01:31:05.860
as you show here by the fluctuation of CDK2 low and

1528
01:31:06.010 --> 01:31:07.790
high dribbling activity.

1529
01:31:08.810 --> 01:31:12.770
So this data suggested that the G12C inhibitor might prime

1530
01:31:12.810 --> 01:31:15.330
aurora kinase A-dependent mitotic catastrophe.

1531
01:31:17.210 --> 01:31:20.290
How does G12C prime this catastrophe?

1532
01:31:20.330 --> 01:31:24.270
So to answer that question, we pretreat the cell with G12C

1533
01:31:24.290 --> 01:31:27.880
inhibitor and aurora kinase A inhibitor and synchronize them

1534
01:31:27.990 --> 01:31:31.890
at the prometaphase, and then did mitotic shake-off,

1535
01:31:32.210 --> 01:31:34.330
and then watch the cell afterwards.

1536
01:31:34.570 --> 01:31:38.000
And as you can see, the vehicle-treated cell pass through mitosis very

1537
01:31:38.470 --> 01:31:41.790
normally. G12C can slow down mitosis for a little bit,

1538
01:31:42.330 --> 01:31:44.850
and the aurora kinase A cause mitotic arrest.

1539
01:31:46.570 --> 01:31:50.420
Prolonged treatment of the aurora kinase A inhibitor actually create these

1540
01:31:50.470 --> 01:31:54.220
polyploid cells, suggesting that aurora kinase A is

1541
01:31:54.270 --> 01:31:56.430
